			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Charm Kiting at 38 - what am I doing wrong?<a name="22480"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Feb 19 04 12:43 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>One thing I preach every time I get the chance, and will be VERY important for you when you get the 60 second lvl 39 Charm song:
<br />

<br />
IF YOU GET RESISTS OR EARLY BREAKS ON CHARM OR MEZ, USE A WIND INSTRUMENT TO INCREASE THE MR DEBUFF!!!
<br />

<br />
Sorry to scream that.  But every time I see posts about early charm breaks and resists etc. I see people talking about CHA.  That's all well and good, but is completely unproven.  The only things that are PROVEN about CHA is that a secondary check against your CHA is done on a resisted Lull attempt, to determine whether the mob will aggro or not.
<br />

<br />
Our charm and mez songs have a Magic Resist debuff component.  Not only does the mob make an MR check to see if it will resist the initial landing of the song, but A MR CHECK HAPPENS EVERY TICK to see if the song will stick, or break early.
<br />

<br />
So... at lvl 27, Solon's Song of the Sirens debuffs MR by 4 without a Flute.  Equipping a Bloodstained Flute when you land it, with a 2.2 modifier, 4 * 2.2 = 8.8 or 9 MR debuffed.  This may not seem like a huge difference, but at least this is confirmed mathematical fact.
<br />

<br />
39 Charm without flute = 5 MR debuff.  With 2.2 Flute = 10.5 (not sure if this rounds up or down, actually)  At lvl 40 our mez song does 9 MR debuff without flute, with 2.2 = 19 MR debuff.  On a mez, this makes a HUGE difference in being able to refresh the next one.
<br />

<br />
/sermon off
<br />

<br />
It may be that those 18 seconds are just going by faster than you think.  Or, your charms could indeed be breaking early.  When you use your 39 Charm song, it will be much more obivous when it breaks early.  Just remember the instrument thing when people start asking you about your CHA, hehe.
<br />

<br />
Once your charm breaks, it is actually quite normal that you end up with all the aggro of your pet's former target.  One way to combat this is distance.  If you are WELL out of melee range of your target mob, he is MUCH more likely to aggro your pet instead of you.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="SmallText"><hr size="1" align="left" width="15%"><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=564823">Scherzo Glissando </a><BR>
Maestro, Molto Espressivo</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
